{% block containment %}
## 🚨 Containment Steps – Port Scan / Reconnaissance Response

> **⚡ Execute all phases in order. Tick every checkbox. If the scanner is internal, treat as insider threat – escalate immediately.**

---

### 🔴 Phase 1 · Immediate Traffic Control & Evidence Capture `(T+0 → T+10 min)`

> Goal: Throttle the scanner, capture evidence, and deploy deception before the attacker completes enumeration.

- [ ] **Start full packet capture on the targeted subnet** – Capture all traffic from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` to `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}` for `{{ capture_duration | default("300s") }}`:

  ```bash
  # tcpdump – capture scanner traffic
  tcpdump -i {{ capture_interface | default("eth0") }} \
    src host {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} \
    -w /tmp/portscan_{{ source_ip | default("scanner") }}_$(date +%s).pcap \
    -G {{ capture_duration | default("300") }} -W 1 &
  echo "PCAP PID: $!"
  ```

- [ ] **Fingerprint the scanner tool** – Identify the scanning tool from packet timing, TTL, and flag patterns:
  ```bash
  # Analyse captured PCAP
  p0f -r /tmp/portscan_{{ source_ip | default("scanner") }}_*.pcap
  # Check IDS alert for scanner signature
  grep "{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}" \
    {{ ids_alert_log | default("/var/log/snort/alert") }} | \
    grep -i "nmap\|masscan\|zmap\|scanner" | head -10
  ```
  Detected tool: `{{ scanner_tool_fingerprint | default("Run analysis above") }}`

- [ ] **Apply rate-limit to scanner IP** – Throttle but do NOT immediately block (preserves deception opportunity):
  ```bash
  # iptables – rate-limit to 5 packets/sec from scanner
  iptables -I INPUT -s {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} \
    -m limit --limit 5/sec --limit-burst 10 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -I INPUT -s {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} -j DROP
  ```

- [ ] **Block scanner IP at perimeter after capture window** – Once PCAP is secured, apply full block for `{{ block_duration | default("3600") }}s`:
  ```bash
  iptables -I INPUT -s {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} -j DROP
  iptables -I OUTPUT -d {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} -j DROP
  # Rollback tag: unblock_scan_{{ source_ip | default("ip") }}
  ```

{% if sdn_enabled | default(true) %}
- [ ] **Push SDN flow rule** – Drop packets from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` network-wide via PhantomNet SDN controller:
  ```bash
  # PhantomNet SDN API
  phantomnet-sdn flow add \
    --src {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}/32 \
    --action drop \
    --priority 1000 \
    --ttl {{ block_duration | default("3600") }}
  ```
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Deploy `{{ honeypot_count | default(3) }}` deception honeypots** – Deploy additional `{{ honeypot_type | default("deception_mesh") }}` nodes in `{{ target_subnet | default("the scanned subnet") }}` to capture scanner activity and fingerprint attacker intent:
  ```bash
  # PhantomNet honeypot deployment
  phantomnet-honeypot deploy \
    --type {{ honeypot_type | default("deception_mesh") }} \
    --count {{ honeypot_count | default(3) }} \
    --subnet {{ target_subnet | default("<target_subnet>") }} \
    --mode {{ deception_mode | default("aggressive_deception") }}
  ```

- [ ] **Activate `{{ deception_mode | default("aggressive_deception") }}` mode** – Configure honeypots to actively engage the scanner with false service banners and intentionally attractive fake services.

{% if geo_block_country is defined and geo_block_country %}
- [ ] **Apply geo-block for `{{ geo_block_country }}`** – If scan originates externally from `{{ geo_block_country }}`, apply upstream geo-block.
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Alert SOC** – Send `{{ alert_level | default("HIGH") }}` alert:
  *"Port scan from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` ({{ scanner_tool_fingerprint | default("tool unknown") }}) – `{{ port_count | default("?") }}` ports on `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}`. Honeypots deployed. Evidence captured."*

{% if escalate_to_ciso | default(false) %}
- [ ] **🔴 Escalate to CISO** – Scan scope or internal origin requires executive notification.
{% endif %}

---

### 🔒 Phase 2 · Network Segmentation Review `(T+10 → T+90 min)`

> Goal: Determine if the scanner reached segments it should not have, and tighten segmentation.

#### 2a. Segment Reachability Analysis

- [ ] **Map which segments/VLANs were reachable from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}`**
  ```bash
  # NetFlow analysis – which internal hosts responded to the scanner?
  nfdump -r {{ netflow_dir | default("/var/cache/nfdump/") }} \
    -t "{{ detection_time | default("2026-01-01 00:00:00") }}" \
    "src ip {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} and flags S" \
    -s dstip:p -n 50 -o extended
  ```

- [ ] **Identify cross-segment flows** – Flag any scan traffic that traversed firewall zone boundaries:
{% if network_segments is defined and network_segments %}
  **Segments requiring review:**
  | Segment / VLAN | Zone | Expected Access | Actual Access | Action |
  |---|---|---|---|---|
{% for seg in network_segments %}
  | `{{ seg }}` | `{{ firewall_zone | default("Unknown") }}` | ☐ Verify | ☐ Audit | ☐ Restrict if needed |
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
  ```bash
  # Query firewall logs for cross-zone traffic from scanner IP
  grep "{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}" \
    {{ fw_log_path | default("/var/log/firewall.log") }} | \
    grep -v "DENY\|DROP" | \
    awk '{print $NF}' | sort -u
  ```
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Check for missing inter-VLAN ACLs** – Verify that the core switch / router has ACLs preventing unauthorised inter-VLAN routing:
  ```bash
  # Cisco IOS example
  show ip access-lists | grep -A5 "{{ vlan_id | default("PROD_VLAN") }}"
  # Verify VLAN {{ vlan_id | default("<vlan>") }} cannot reach management VLAN
  show vlan brief
  show interfaces trunk
  ```

- [ ] **Verify firewall zone policy between scanner origin and target** – Review the rule set for `{{ firewall_zone | default("the affected zone") }}`:
  ```bash
  # iptables zone review
  iptables -L FORWARD -n -v | grep "{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}"
  # pfSense / OPNsense: check firewall rules via API or UI for zone {{ firewall_zone | default("N/A") }}
  ```

- [ ] **Identify and close unauthorised firewall rules** – Document any `ACCEPT` rules that should not exist between the scanner's origin segment and the scanned subnet.

#### 2b. Segmentation Hardening

- [ ] **Implement or tighten inter-VLAN ACLs** – Apply deny-by-default between segments with explicit allow only for required traffic flows:
  ```bash
  # Linux (iptables) – deny inter-VLAN default
  iptables -I FORWARD -i {{ scanner_vlan_if | default("vlan10") }} \
    -o {{ target_vlan_if | default("vlan20") }} -j DROP
  # Allow only specific required ports (e.g. TCP 443 from web tier to DB tier)
  iptables -I FORWARD -i {{ scanner_vlan_if | default("vlan10") }} \
    -o {{ target_vlan_if | default("vlan20") }} -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT
  ```

- [ ] **Enable port security on access switches** – Limit MAC addresses per port to prevent scanner pivoting via ARP spoofing.

- [ ] **Verify micro-segmentation rules** – If SDN/NSX/ACI is deployed, confirm micro-segmentation policies are enforced for `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}`.

- [ ] **Document segmentation gap findings** – Record all discovered gaps in a network segmentation review ticket for remediation tracking.

#### 2c. Internal vs External Scan Classification

- [ ] **Determine if scan is internal or external**:
  - External (`{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` is a public IP): Attacker has perimeter access → escalate, check for prior intrusion
  - Internal: Potential insider threat, compromised host, or misconfigured tool → isolate source host immediately
  ```bash
  # Check if source IP is RFC1918 (internal)
  python3 -c "import ipaddress; print(ipaddress.ip_address('{{ source_ip | default("0.0.0.0") }}').is_private)"
  ```

- [ ] **If internal scan** – Isolate `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` host from the network pending investigation:
  ```bash
  # SDN isolation
  phantomnet-sdn isolate --host {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}
  # Or: disable switchport
  # interface GigabitEthernet0/X
  #   shutdown
  ```

---

### 🔍 Phase 3 · Exposed Service Audit `(T+90 min → T+4 hours)`

> Goal: Document every service exposed to the scanner; close everything that should not be public.

#### 3a. Open Port Inventory

- [ ] **Perform authorised scan of `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}`** from a trusted host – establish a ground-truth open-port inventory:
  ```bash
  # Full TCP + top UDP scan from approved scan host
  nmap -sS -sU --top-ports 1000 -sV -O --script=banner \
    -oA /tmp/auth_scan_{{ target_subnet | default("subnet") }}_$(date +%s) \
    {{ target_subnet | default("<target_subnet>") }}

  # Compare with previous baseline (if available)
  ndiff {{ baseline_scan | default("/tmp/baseline.xml") }} \
    /tmp/auth_scan_{{ target_subnet | default("subnet") }}_*.xml
  ```

- [ ] **Cross-reference with CMDB / asset inventory** – Every open port must map to an approved service in the CMDB. Flag any unregistered services.

- [ ] **Identify and close unexpected open ports**:
{% if exposed_services is defined and exposed_services %}
  **Services found open that require immediate review:**
  | Service / Port | Host | Expected? | Action |
  |---|---|---|---|
{% for svc in exposed_services %}
  | `{{ svc }}` | `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}` | ❌ No | Close immediately |
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
  ```bash
  # Compare discovered ports against approved allow-list
  # Approved ports: {{ allowed_ports | default(["80", "443", "22"]) | join(", ") }}
  nmap -p {{ allowed_ports | default(["80", "443", "22"]) | join(",") }} \
    --open {{ target_subnet | default("<target_subnet>") }}
  ```
{% endif %}

#### 3b. Service Hardening Checklist

- [ ] **Disable / firewall all non-essential services** – For each unexpected open port found:
  ```bash
  # Stop the service
  systemctl stop <service_name>
  systemctl disable <service_name>
  # Block the port at host firewall
  iptables -I INPUT -p tcp --dport <port> -j DROP
  ```

- [ ] **Remove default and test services** – Audit for common unnecessary services:
  - [ ] Telnet (`23`) – must be disabled everywhere
  - [ ] FTP (`21`) – disable; use SFTP on port `22` instead
  - [ ] SNMP v1/v2 (`161`) – disable or upgrade to SNMPv3 with auth
  - [ ] RDP (`3389`) exposed to internet – restrict to VPN only
  - [ ] Management interfaces (`8080`, `8443`, `9090`) – restrict to management VLAN only
  - [ ] Database ports (`3306`, `5432`, `1433`) exposed externally – block immediately

- [ ] **Harden service banners** – Remove version information from service banners to reduce attacker intelligence:
  ```bash
  # Nginx – remove server version
  echo "server_tokens off;" >> /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
  nginx -s reload

  # OpenSSH – remove banner
  sed -i 's/^#*Banner.*/Banner none/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config
  systemctl reload sshd
  ```

- [ ] **Review and tighten firewall allow-list** – Apply default-deny + explicit allow for every segment in `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}`:
  ```bash
  # Verify iptables default policy is DROP
  iptables -L INPUT --line-numbers | head -5
  # Should show: Chain INPUT (policy DROP)
  iptables -P INPUT DROP
  iptables -P FORWARD DROP
  ```

- [ ] **Enable TCP SYN cookies** – Protect against SYN-flood follow-up after reconnaissance:
  ```bash
  echo "net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf
  sysctl -p
  ```

#### 3c. IDS/IPS Signature Update

- [ ] **Update IDS/IPS (`{{ iids_sensor | default("PhantomNet IDS") }}`) signatures** for the scanner fingerprint:
  ```bash
  # Snort / Suricata – add scanner-specific rule
  cat >> /etc/snort/rules/local.rules << 'EOF'
  alert tcp {{ source_ip | default("any") }} any -> $HOME_NET any \
    (msg:"PORT SCAN - {{ scanner_tool_fingerprint | default("known scanner") }}"; \
     flags:S; threshold: type threshold, track by_src, count 20, seconds 60; \
     sid:9000100; rev:1;)
  EOF
  snort -T -c /etc/snort/snort.conf  # test config
  systemctl restart snort
  ```

- [ ] **Add scanner IP to IDS watchlist** – Ensure all future traffic from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` is monitored at elevated sensitivity.

- [ ] **Review honeypot interaction logs** – Analyse which honeypot services attracted the scanner:
  ```bash
  # PhantomNet honeypot logs
  phantomnet-honeypot logs \
    --filter src={{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} \
    --since {{ detection_time | default("48h") }} \
    --output /tmp/honeypot_{{ source_ip | default("scanner") }}.json
  ```

---

### 🛡️ Phase 4 · Deception Enhancement & Hardening `(T+4 hours → Close)`

> Goal: Convert the incident into intelligence; harden posture to prevent follow-on exploitation.

#### 4a. Threat Intelligence Extraction

- [ ] **Submit scanner IP to threat intelligence feeds**:
  - [ ] VirusTotal IP report for `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}`
  - [ ] AbuseIPDB lookup and report submission
  - [ ] Shodan: check what services `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` exposes
  - [ ] PhantomNet internal TI feed: add IOC with tag `port_scan_{{ scan_type | default("SYN") }}`

- [ ] **Correlate with known scanner / botnet lists** – Check if `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` appears in:
  - Shadowserver scanning infrastructure lists
  - Censys / Shodan known scanners
  - SANS Internet Storm Center top-scanning IPs

- [ ] **Extract scanner tool TTPs** – Document observed scan timing, rate, flag patterns, and tool signature for the threat model.

#### 4b. Deception Posture Update

- [ ] **Promote high-interaction honeypots** – Convert `{{ honeypot_count | default(3) }}` deployed honeypots from passive to active-interaction mode to learn follow-on exploitation intent.

- [ ] **Add fake services to attract follow-on exploitation** – Deploy listening services on ports that were scanned and found "open" in the scan (to capture payloads):
  ```bash
  # netcat listener (for research/detection)
  for port in {{ open_bait_ports | default("8080 8443 9200") }}; do
    nc -lkp $port >> /tmp/bait_${port}_$(date +%s).log &
  done
  ```

- [ ] **Update deception topology** – Modify network topology visible to scanners (via ARP spoofing / SDN) to make the network appear larger than it is.

#### 4c. Security Posture Hardening

- [ ] **Enable egress filtering** – Ensure outbound scanning is also blocked (to prevent compromised hosts from being used as scan pivots):
  ```bash
  iptables -I OUTPUT -p tcp --syn -m limit \
    --limit 10/min --limit-burst 50 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --syn -j DROP
  ```

- [ ] **Configure IDS port-scan detection thresholds**:
  ```bash
  # Snort/Suricata threshold for portscan detection
  # Trigger if > {{ port_count_threshold | default(50) }} ports per minute from single source
  ```

- [ ] **Schedule periodic authorised network scans** – Set up monthly vulnerability scans of `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}` to maintain an up-to-date open-port baseline.

#### 4d. Incident Close-out

- [ ] **Create incident ticket in `{{ ticket_system | default("Jira") }}`** – Project: `{{ ticket_project | default("SEC") }}`
  Summary: *"Port Scan: `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` (`{{ scanner_tool_fingerprint | default("unknown tool") }}`) – `{{ port_count | default("?") }}` ports on `{{ target_subnet | default("<subnet>") }}`"*

- [ ] **Generate scan intelligence report** – Document discovered topology, open ports, and scanner TTPs.

- [ ] **Update network asset inventory** – Reconcile any newly discovered services with CMDB.

- [ ] **Publish IOC to threat sharing** – Export scanner IP and tool fingerprint as STIX bundle.

- [ ] **Schedule 48-hour post-incident review** – Debrief with Network Ops, SOC, and if internal, HR/Legal.

